class Solution {
    public boolean checkInclusion(String s1, String s2) {
        int len1 = s1.length(), len2 = s2.length();
        if (len1 > len2) return false;

        int[] count1 = new int[26];
        int[] count2 = new int[26];

        for (int i = 0; i < len1; i++) {
            count1[s1.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
            count2[s2.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
        }

        if (Arrays.equals(count1, count2)) return true;

        for (int i = len1; i < len2; i++) {
            count2[s2.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
            count2[s2.charAt(i - len1) - 'a']--;
            if (Arrays.equals(count1, count2)) return true;
        }

        return false;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(26 * n) = O(n)
space complexity: O(26) = O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses sliding window with fixed-size frequency arrays (26 counters) to compare character counts in constant time. Arrays.equals is O(26) per check, but overall linear in input size. Minimal memory footprint and no heavy operations.

